How to do it?:

Notice: In this assignment, all the plot should have title, caption, and axis labels.

  1. Use the dataset by of covid 19 by WHO at https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv. Find the three countries with the most numbers of deaths by Covid-19.
library(tidyverse) 

df <- read_csv('WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv')

Hint:

  • Use filter to select the most current date
#removed Cote D'Ivoire's data because R was having trouble reading the 
#country name

#This code block contains suggested codes from Chat GPT since I couldn't find
#applicable codes from the Assignment 9 slides. 

df <- df %>%
  filter(Country_code != "CI")


df_filt <- df %>%
  group_by(Country_code) %>%
  filter(Date_reported == max(Date_reported, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()
  • Pipe with arrange(-Cumulative_deaths) to rank the data by the number of cumulative deaths
df_filt %>% 

arrange(-Cumulative_deaths)

  1. Use transition_reveal to make a plot revealing the number of deaths in the three countries with the most numbers of deaths
library(gganimate) 

df %>% 
  filter(Country_code %in% c('US','BR','IN')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=Cumulative_deaths,
            x=Date_reported,
            color=Country_code))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  geom_text(aes(label = Cumulative_deaths), 
            hjust = -.1, size=5) +
  transition_reveal(Date_reported)

#The three countries with the highest deaths per cases are Yemen, Sudan, and #the Syrian Arab Republic.

  1. Use transition_reveal to make a plot revealing the number of deaths per cases of the US, Italy and Mexico.
df <- df %>%
  mutate(deaths_per_cases= Cumulative_deaths / Cumulative_cases) 


df %>% 
  filter(Country_code %in% c('US','IT','MX')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=deaths_per_cases,
            x=Date_reported,
            color=Country_code))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  geom_text(aes(label = deaths_per_cases), 
            hjust = -.1, size=5) +
  transition_reveal(as.numeric(Date_reported))

  1. Import the following data https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/vaccinations/vaccinations.csv
df3 <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/vaccinations/vaccinations.csv')

Use transition_reveal to plot the total vaccinations per hundred by level of income. Hint: the levels of income are identified in the location variable. Put a short comment on the caption of the plot.

#comment out at end so file would knit
#install.packages(c("dplyr", "wbstats"))
library(dplyr)
library(wbstats)
library(ggplot2)
library(gganimate)
library(tidyr) 
wb_countries <- wb_countries()
names(wb_countries)
##  [1] "iso3c"              "iso2c"              "country"           
##  [4] "capital_city"       "longitude"          "latitude"          
##  [7] "region_iso3c"       "region_iso2c"       "region"            
## [10] "admin_region_iso3c" "admin_region_iso2c" "admin_region"      
## [13] "income_level_iso3c" "income_level_iso2c" "income_level"      
## [16] "lending_type_iso3c" "lending_type_iso2c" "lending_type"
df3 <- df3 %>%
  left_join(
    wb_countries %>% select(iso3c, income_level),
    by = c("iso_code" = "iso3c")
  )
df3_clean <- df3 %>%
  filter(!is.na(income_level) & !is.na(total_vaccinations_per_hundred))
library(gifski)
library(png)
df3_clean <- df3_clean %>%
  filter(income_level %in% c('High income',
                                 'Low income',
                                 'Lower middle income',
                                 'Upper middle income'))
df3_clean %>%
  count(income_level)
## # A tibble: 4  2
##   income_level            n
##   <chr>               <int>
## 1 High income         36334
## 2 Low income           1781
## 3 Lower middle income 10612
## 4 Upper middle income 16438
df3_clean %>% 
  filter(income_level %in% c('High income','Low income','Lower middle income','Upper middle income')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=total_vaccinations_per_hundred,
            x=date,
            color=income_level))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  geom_text(aes(label = total_vaccinations_per_hundred), 
            check_overlap = TRUE, size=3) +
  transition_reveal(date) +
  labs(x = 'Date', 
     y = 'Total Vaccinations Per Hundred',
     color = 'Income Level',
     title = 'Plot of Total Vaccinations/100 by Date and Income Level', 
       caption = 'This plot shows in color how overall, wealthier countries tended 
                  to have higher vaccination rates.')
